    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName>
                <date>June 8<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1852</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <sic>
                    <addressee>Revd Isaac Leesor</addressee>
                </sic>
            </p>
            <p>
                <placeName>Philadelphia Pa</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Sir<lb/> The temporal affairs of the<lb/> synagogue are so frequently under the
                eye of our spiritual advisers<lb/> that those who are best informed on either head
                can give the best<lb/> advice on both, with this view I am soliciting today from
                many<lb/> of our public new information and opinions on a question that<lb/> has
                been the cause of worse than injury to our public, institut-<lb/>tions for it has
                invaded the domestic hearth The problem is<lb/> Should our congregations (and do
                they usually) keep, rent, sell,<lb/> lease or donate their seats or should they be
                free to all and<lb/> how as to members, and non members, I am chairman of the<lb/>
                committee to whom this nice question has been referred myself<lb/> and associates
                are solicitous, that we present a law having<lb/> the sanction of experience and
                statistics, doing equal and<lb/> exact justice to all our members requiring the same
                from<lb/> them towards the corporation its revenue and towards each<lb/> other, for
                as I should have before remarked we already<lb/> have the incubus of <hi
                    rend="underline">non seat holder</hi> and <hi rend="underline">seat holder</hi>
                in<lb/> our congregation, and I have started the question so that<lb/> we may enter
                our new edifice with clean hands if even<lb/> not with pure hearts n b this letter
                we must leave with our<lb/> pastors (?) What I would wish from you is this<lb/> 1<hi
                    rend="sup">st</hi> all printed and other recorded evidence as to how this<lb/>
                subject is managed in <placeName>Phila.</placeName> and in other places where<lb/>
                you have lived with remarks as to how it works<lb/> 2<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> your
                opinion as to <hi rend="underline">how</hi> it <hi rend="underline">ought to be</hi>
                managed</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>Your early reply will be valued In the multitude of<lb/> counsel there is wisdom and
                though this question is<lb/> a proper one for the laity yet affairs on this
                continent<lb/> in Jewish legislation have been generally so thoughtlessly<lb/>
                managed I am a little anxious and curious to learn what<lb/> portion has had the
                most foresight</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">My excuse for not writing you at length must be that<lb/> I have
                several letters of this tenor to write today besides<lb/> yourself I address
                    <persName>Revds S M Isaacs</persName> &amp; <persName>I K
                Gutheim</persName><lb/> and <persName>Drs Wise</persName>,
                    <persName>Raphael</persName>, and <persName>Lilienthal</persName> besides
                some<lb/> of our laity conversant with the subject</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">With Sincere wishes</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">I am Yours <sic>Fraternaly</sic></p>
            <p rend="indent(5)"><persName role="author">Lewis Abraham</persName>.</p>
            <pb n="2V"/>
            <p>
                <sic>
                    <addressee>Revd Isaac Leesor</addressee>
                </sic>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <placeName>Pa.</placeName>
            </p>
